  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2238678157" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2238678157" />
    <a title="Mindi" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/6157592-mindi"><img alt="Mindi" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1538422738p2/6157592.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2238678157?book_show_action=true">Jan 25, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Mindi" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Mindi" href="/user/show/6157592-mindi">Mindi</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780316404068" href="/book/show/18129494-the-killer-inside-me">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2238678157" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2358499687263159186">The Killer Inside Me is unlike any other book I&apos;ve read. Published in 1952, it&apos;s a pulpy crime noir novel with a twist. The protagonist is no hard boiled detective hot on the trail of a killer, but rather the killer himself. Lou Ford is the Deputy Sheriff of a small town in Texas, and he&apos;s also a sociopathic murderer. And the reader gets to be inside his head for 229 pages. That&apos;s a very uncomfortable place to be. (Mild spoilers ahead, so if you want to go into this book knowing very little, sto</span>
  <span id="freeText2358499687263159186" style="display:none">The Killer Inside Me is unlike any other book I've read. Published in 1952, it's a pulpy crime noir novel with a twist. The protagonist is no hard boiled detective hot on the trail of a killer, but rather the killer himself. Lou Ford is the Deputy Sheriff of a small town in Texas, and he's also a sociopathic murderer. And the reader gets to be inside his head for 229 pages. That's a very uncomfortable place to be. (Mild spoilers ahead, so if you want to go into this book knowing very little, stop right here.)<br /><br />To be honest I'm astonished this book got published at all in 1952. There's a crudeness to it that surprised me every time Thompson wrote a sentence that had to be taboo for 1950's America. And yet, that crudeness is necessary at times, because we are in the mind of Lou Ford, and crudeness is quite at home there. Lou kills a number of people for varying reasons throughout the book, and he's fully convinced that no matter what he'll get away with it. Lou thinks he has everyone fooled, that's he's the nicest guy in Central City, but he soon becomes desperate and sloppy, and it doesn't take long for the rest of the sheriff's department to figure out what's really going on in town.<br /><br />Lou's attitude, his childhood, which is pieced together slowly through the novel, and his outlook on life are all very twisted. And his crimes are especially violent and disturbing, especially considering we have a front row seat for each and every one of them. Lou kills if he thinks it's necessary, and always to save his own hide. I won't go into the plot here, but it starts with a badly planned blackmail scheme and ends with Lou unraveling completely. <br /><br />The Killer Inside Me is a quick read that leaves you feeling like you need a palate cleanser book afterwards. Being inside the mind of Lou Ford is daunting and unpleasant, but this book left an impact on me that I know I won't soon forget.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2358499687263159186" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


